The paper focuses on developing a methodology for incorporating interactive, 3D-rendered product configurations into a conjoint-like framework to optimize visual design. This involves using machine learning algorithms to adaptively update product designs and a novel, adaptive "bi-level" query task to estimate individuals' visual design form preferences and their trade-offs against traditional elements such as price and product features. The paper's emphasis on human-computer interaction (HCI) and artificial intelligence (AI) suggests that cs.HC and cs.AI are the most likely sub-categories. The use of 3D rendering and geometry also suggests that cs.GR and cs.CV are relevant sub-categories. Finally, the use of machine learning algorithms and optimization techniques suggests that cs.LG is a possible sub-category.
